<!--
    Demo Task 05 - Post-resolution archive (Closed / Other)
    ====================================================================

    Synthetic seed record for the case-management POC scoped application.
    This file is the FIFTH of the 8-task demo dataset; together with
    tasks 01 through 04 and tasks 06 through 08, it satisfies the AAP
    requirement (Section 0.7.4) of providing demo tasks that exercise
    the resolve-blocker and resolve-success gates on both case-type
    flows. The complete 8-task fixture matrix:

        Task 01 - Open        / Investigation / parent case 03 (In Progress GI)
        Task 02 - Closed      / Investigation / parent case 03 (In Progress GI)
        Task 03 - Open        / Follow-up     / parent case 04 (Pending GI)
        Task 04 - Closed      / Investigation / parent case 05 (Resolved GI)
        Task 05 - Closed      / Other         / parent case 05 (Resolved GI)  ## THIS FILE
        Task 06 - In Progress / Investigation / parent case 08 (In Progress Complaint)
        Task 07 - Open        / Investigation / parent case 08 (In Progress Complaint)
        Task 08 - Closed      / Review        / parent case 09 (Resolved Complaint)

    The 8-task dataset thus exercises:
      * All 4 task types - this task is the ONE AND ONLY canonical
        demonstrator for the `Other` task type (the catch-all for tasks
        that do not fit Investigation, Review, or Follow-up). Per AAP
        Section 0.5.7, the case_task type Choice list defines exactly
        four values - Investigation, Review, Follow-up, Other - and
        without this task the dataset would lack any `Other` exercise
        (Investigation appears on tasks 01, 02, 04, 06, 07; Review
        appears on task 08; Follow-up appears on task 03; Other appears
        only here). This task is the LOAD-BEARING PROOF that the
        `Other` choice value is registered, accepted by the table-level
        dictionary entry, and surfaces correctly on the form.
      * All 3 task statuses (Open, In Progress, Closed) - this task
        contributes the THIRD of four Closed tasks (the others are
        tasks 02, 04, and 08); the Closed status is the terminal task
        status that satisfies the validate_resolved_transition subflow's
        "all child tasks must be Closed" gate, allowing the parent case
        to be transitioned from In Progress to Resolved.
      * 5 unique parent cases (03, 04, 05, 08, 09) - this task is the
        SECOND child of case 05 (the first being task 04); together,
        tasks 04 + 05 give case 05 ZERO non-Closed child tasks
        (both Closed), demonstrating that the resolve gate's
        GlideRecord query correctly returns zero rows and ALLOWS the
        In Progress -> Resolved transition. Case 05 is already in
        Resolved status in its own seed record; this task's existence
        as a Closed child of case 05 ensures the resolve gate's
        precondition was met at the time case 05 was resolved (i.e.,
        when an internal user demos by attempting to "re-resolve"
        case 05 by stepping it back through the lifecycle, the
        resolve gate will permit the transition because all child
        tasks are Closed).
      * Both flow paths (General Inquiry and Complaint) - tasks 04 + 05
        together test the GENERAL INQUIRY flow's resolve-SUCCESS path;
        tasks 01 + 02 test the GENERAL INQUIRY flow's resolve-blocker
        path; tasks 06 + 07 test the COMPLAINT flow's resolve-blocker
        path; task 08 tests the COMPLAINT flow's resolve-success path.
      * Both resolve outcomes (BLOCKED via at least one non-Closed task,
        and SUCCESS via zero non-Closed tasks) - this task is the
        SECOND enabler of the General Inquiry resolve-success path
        (paired with task 04), demonstrating that when ALL child tasks
        carry status=Closed, the validate_resolved_transition subflow
        returns zero rows and the transition is permitted.

    Lifecycle position - WHY Closed / Other / parent General Inquiry case
    Resolved is meaningful:
      Per AAP Section 0.5.5 the resolve gate's GlideRecord query
      executed inside the validate_resolved_transition subflow is:

          var gr = new GlideRecord('x_[scope]_case_task');
          gr.addQuery('case', current.sys_id);
          gr.addQuery('status', '!=', 'Closed');
          gr.query();
          if (gr.next()) {
              // BLOCK: surface the verbatim error message
              //   "All tasks must be closed before resolving this case."
          } else {
              // ALLOW: zero non-Closed tasks - case may be Resolved
          }

      Case 05 is in Resolved status with type=General Inquiry. Both of
      its child tasks (task 04 and THIS task 05) are Closed, so the
      query "case = case 05 AND status != Closed" returns ZERO rows.
      The subflow ALLOWS the In Progress -> Resolved transition. THIS
      TASK + TASK 04 ARE THE CANONICAL RESOLVE-SUCCESS PAIR FOR THE
      GENERAL INQUIRY FLOW. Where task 08 performs this role for case
      09 on the Complaint flow, this task with task 04 performs the
      same role for case 05 on the General Inquiry flow. Note: this
      pairing is symmetric to the resolve-blocker pair (tasks 01 + 02
      on case 03), but with all child tasks Closed instead of all
      non-Closed.

      The Other task type captures actions that do not fit any of the
      three primary categories (Investigation, Review, Follow-up). Per
      the AAP's Section 0.5.7 Choice list for case_task type, Other is
      the catch-all fourth value - intended for administrative,
      housekeeping, archival, or other miscellaneous activities that
      arise during case handling but are not part of the core
      investigation/review/follow-up lifecycle. The "Post-resolution
      archive" subject makes this catch-all role explicit and
      semantically justifies why a task of type Other exists on a
      Resolved case: AFTER the case was resolved, an archival task
      was logged to capture administrative cleanup (e.g., archiving
      documents, updating internal records, marking the case as
      handed-off to records management). This archival activity is
      neither an investigation, nor a review, nor a follow-up - it
      is post-resolution housekeeping, which is the canonical Other
      pattern. The Closed status is consistent with this completed-
      housekeeping semantic: the archival task was created, performed,
      and closed, leaving zero open work on case 05.

      The -1 day due_date reflects that the archival task was due
      yesterday (relative to the build environment date 2026-05-01,
      i.e., 2026-04-30) and was completed on or before that date.
      This matches task 04's -1 day due_date - both tasks were
      due/completed at approximately the same time, before the case
      was resolved. The relative date pattern uses negative offsets
      (1 day ago) for completed tasks, consistent with Closed status
      semantics (a task that has been started, performed, and closed,
      with a target completion date that is now in the past).

